    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>What ABV Means and Why Brewers Care</h2>
      <p>
        Alcohol by volume is the percentage of pure ethanol in the finished beverage by volume. A 5 percent ABV beer contains 5 mL of ethanol in every 100 mL of beer. Knowing the ABV of every batch matters for far more than label accuracy: it tells you whether your fermentation finished cleanly, whether your yeast ran out of nitrogen or sugar, and whether the recipe behaved like the expected style. For homebrewers it is the headline number every batch is judged by, and for licensed brewers and winemakers it has direct legal and tax implications because excise duty in most countries is calculated on alcohol content.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Simple vs Advanced ABV Formulas</h2>
      <p>
        The simple formula ABV equals OG minus FG times 131.25 is the one most homebrew books quote because the math is easy and the answer is good enough for typical 1.040 to 1.060 worts. The advanced formula uses ABV equals 76.08 times OG minus FG divided by 1.775 minus OG, all multiplied by FG divided by 0.794, and corrects for the non-linear relationship between gravity drop and alcohol production at higher strengths. For a 1.090 imperial stout the advanced formula returns roughly half a percent more ABV than the simple version, and that gap matters for accurate label compliance, judging in competition, and tax reporting if you sell the beer.
      </p>

      <h2>Original and Final Gravity in Practice</h2>
      <p>
        Original gravity is read in a chilled wort sample just before pitching yeast. Use either a calibrated hydrometer or a refractometer, but always remember to correct the reading for temperature and, with a refractometer, for the wort correction factor. Final gravity is read after fermentation has fully stopped, which usually means 10 to 14 days for an ale and 4 to 6 weeks for a lager. Confirm the FG by reading the same value on two consecutive days because a beer that is still slowly fermenting will look done one day and drop a point the next. Hydrometers are the most reliable tool for FG readings because the alcohol present skews refractometer readings.
      </p>

      <h2>Apparent vs Real Attenuation</h2>
      <p>
        The attenuation number returned here is apparent attenuation, calculated from the change in specific gravity. Real attenuation is always a few points higher because the alcohol produced during fermentation is less dense than water and pulls the apparent gravity reading down. For practical brewing decisions apparent attenuation is what matters: it tells you how dry the beer finished and whether the yeast strain hit its expected range. Most clean ale strains land 72 to 80 percent, lagers a few points higher, and Belgian, saison, and brettanomyces strains can attenuate 85 to 100 percent, which is what gives those beers their characteristic dryness.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is the formula for ABV from gravity?</h3>
      <p>
        The simple formula is ABV equals OG minus FG times 131.25. The more accurate Miller formula is ABV equals 76.08 times the gravity drop divided by 1.775 minus OG, multiplied by FG over 0.794. The simple formula is fine under 1.070 OG; the advanced formula is more accurate for big beers.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I read original and final gravity?</h3>
      <p>
        Use a hydrometer in a chilled, degassed sample for both readings. Take the OG just before pitching yeast and the FG when fermentation has stopped, confirmed by two consecutive identical readings. Correct hydrometer readings for sample temperature when it differs from 60°F.
      </p>

      <h3>What is apparent attenuation?</h3>
      <p>
        Apparent attenuation is the percentage of sugars the yeast fermented, calculated from the gravity drop. Most ale strains land 72 to 80 percent, lagers 75 to 85 percent, and saisons or brettanomyces strains 85 percent or higher. It is the headline number for whether your fermentation finished.
      </p>

      <h3>What does ABW mean?</h3>
      <p>
        ABW is alcohol by weight and equals roughly ABV times 0.79336 because ethanol is less dense than water. American beer historically used ABW on labels until the 1990s, which is why old beers seem weaker than modern equivalents — a 4% ABW beer is roughly 5% ABV.
      </p>

      <h3>How accurate is this calculator?</h3>
      <p>
        For typical beer strengths the calculator is accurate to within 0.1 to 0.2 percent ABV. The biggest source of error is your gravity readings, not the formula, so use a calibrated hydrometer at the correct temperature for the most reliable result.
      </p>

